WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.420 --> 00:00:01.490
Hello everyone.

00:00:01.490 --> 00:00:06.650
We're here in the Exhibition Model and
Planning Room at the Museum of Modern Art.

00:00:06.650 --> 00:00:07.650
My name is Lana Hum.

00:00:07.650 --> 00:00:11.290
I'm the Director of Exhibition Design and Production.

00:00:11.290 --> 00:00:12.540
My name is Mack Cole-Edelsack.

00:00:12.540 --> 00:00:16.180
I'm Senior Design Manager on the
Exhibition Design and Production team.

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:20.240
Today, we're here to answer your questions
about how we work with curators and artists

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:23.040
to craft the exhibitions you see here at MoMA and

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:25.600
what it means to be a member of
the Exhibition Design team.

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:30.380
We received a lot of great questions from
the trailer we posted a couple of days ago.

00:00:30.390 --> 00:00:32.689
So we'll start with some of those.

00:00:32.689 --> 00:00:36.840
But our producer will also be
passing some questions along to us.

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:38.780
So let's get to the first question.

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:44.540
This is a multiple question, single subject.

00:00:44.549 --> 00:00:47.620
Essentially, what did you study to
become an exhibition designer?

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:53.220
We heard from María López Vlk,
mossykittens, and shkvart.

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:56.600
So what did you study to
become an exhibition designer?

00:00:56.680 --> 00:01:01.420
Well, Mack, I studied the same thing
you studied to become an exhibition designer.

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:04.600
I studied architecture and Mack did as well.

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:09.600
However, I should note that the exhibition
designers at the Museum of Modern Art come

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:13.560
from all different educational backgrounds.

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:18.369
We have among our staff people who
studied industrial design, interior design.

00:01:18.369 --> 00:01:22.670
We have lots of artists on our team as well.

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:27.299
In particular, the carpenters and
the framers and the builders.

00:01:27.299 --> 00:01:29.780
The makers in our department are artists.

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:32.530
Many of them are musicians.

00:01:32.530 --> 00:01:37.100
So I would say that it's a very diverse
background that we come from.

00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:44.340
Did you wanna elaborate on any
other educational experiences that

00:01:44.340 --> 00:01:46.400
I also studied philosophy and religious studies

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.180
which did not necessarily inform Exhibition Design.

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:52.160
I would argue that it does.

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:53.480
But now it certainly does.

00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:57.039
Okay.

00:01:57.040 --> 00:01:59.380
This comes from nataliealan.

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:04.380
What's the best way for a graphic designer
to transition into an exhibition designer?

00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:07.939
By continuing education or experience?

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:10.920
Could you tell us more about how you
work with the Graphic Design team

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:13.140
at MoMA when creating exhibits?

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:14.150
Mack?

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:19.080
Well, I'll focus on the second part which
is how we work with Graphic Design.

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:21.870
And this is true for most of the
departments in the Museum.

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:24.440
We work quite closely with Graphic Design.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:31.620
While they have their own design timeline
and work specifically on title graphics and

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:38.780
in-exhibition graphics, we do model reviews
together and we work together in the space

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:44.049
in terms of placement and scale tests and
just thinking through how the graphics will

00:02:44.049 --> 00:02:47.370
interact with the artwork and the flow of the show.

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:49.080
It's a very integrated process.

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:54.159
So I would say that a graphic designer can
transition into an exhibition designer.

00:02:54.159 --> 00:03:01.310
I mean, I think when you're thinking about
graphic design, you are thinking spatially.

00:03:01.310 --> 00:03:08.470
That's where the Exhibition Design team here
intersects with the Graphic Design team here.

00:03:08.470 --> 00:03:14.220
But I think that we're all being spatial
thinkers when we work together.

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:20.709
But I would recommend for the
transition to do more sculptural things.

00:03:20.709 --> 00:03:28.980
Like perhaps taking a sculpture class
or studying architecture, those things.

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:35.709
And I think when I transitioned from being
a studio art major who focused on drawing,

00:03:35.709 --> 00:03:36.750
I was interested in architecture.

00:03:36.750 --> 00:03:41.140
One of the things that was recommended
to me was to take a sculpture class.

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:48.220
This question comes from YouTube.

00:03:48.230 --> 00:03:53.379
Sanna Chang asks, "What is unique to the
way that MoMA approaches Exhibition Design

00:03:53.379 --> 00:03:55.000
compared to other museums?

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.959
Have you ever been to an exhibition
that was badly designed?

00:03:57.959 --> 00:04:00.480
And if so, what about it was off?

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:05.719
What kinds of skills are needed to
be a good Exhibition Designer?"

00:04:05.719 --> 00:04:06.719
Okay.

00:04:06.719 --> 00:04:08.580
Well, that's several questions.

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:09.900
I'll take on the first.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:16.500
I don't know exactly how exhibition
is done in other museums.

00:04:16.510 --> 00:04:22.500
I find that at MoMA, like the hallmark of
our processes, that we're very collaborative.

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:31.400
I would say that we feel Exhibition
Design is a very critical process.

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:33.780
It's also a very integrated process.

00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:37.920
I think we work very closely with our curators.

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:44.520
We're lucky enough that we're
fully integrated into the process.

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:51.300
I also think that another way that distinguishes
how Exhibition Design is done here at MoMA

00:04:51.300 --> 00:04:58.780
is that we have a full team of people, of
builders that we work very closely with.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:06.990
I think that perhaps at other institutions,
I think I know that at some other institutions,

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:09.900
the building is outsourced.

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:15.670
So it's more of a process that is aligned
with the way architecture is done where you

00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:20.000
have idea phase, a design development phase

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.900
and then you go into a construction document phase.

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:24.940
And then those documents
are handed off to a builder

00:05:24.940 --> 00:05:28.300
and then that's when the building process begins.

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:37.430
We have a much more integrated process, fluid
process where we ideate iteratively and we

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:43.520
go back and forth on the ideas with our builders,
with our full teams of carpenters and painters

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:46.650
and mechanics and framers.

00:05:46.650 --> 00:05:48.060
Yeah.

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:52.120
To the second part of the question, without
necessarily throwing shade on any specific

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:58.180
exhibition, I think we've all experienced
being in a space that didn't feel like it

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:02.100
was either married to what it was trying to do

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:06.680
or felt generous in the way that we might want it to feel.

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:07.920
True.

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:16.380
Or maybe wasn't as considered, well
considered as we would have liked it to be.

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:18.120
Right. Sure.

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:29.080
Krista Kimble and her fifth grade
students in Haymarket, Virginia.

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:34.000
What are some specific ways that you plan
for your exhibit to engage the audience and

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.130
make them feel an emotional connection?

00:06:37.130 --> 00:06:39.100
What a lovely question!

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.170
Did you wanna speak to that?

00:06:43.170 --> 00:06:44.170
Sure.

00:06:44.170 --> 00:06:49.020
I mean, I think, in some ways,
that's what Exhibition Design is.

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:55.600
And so some of the specific things we do are,
for example, work in model and really work

00:06:55.600 --> 00:07:01.580
with the curators and all the other teams on
what it's gonna feel like as we move through

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:07.700
the space that then develops into drawings
and construction documents and eventually

00:07:07.700 --> 00:07:13.370
the in-gallery installation where, again,
those are exactly the kinds of considerations

00:07:13.370 --> 00:07:19.780
along with art history and the curatorial
concept that are coming into play.

00:07:19.780 --> 00:07:25.370
We also work across the other
fields of expertise at the Museum.

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:30.850
We work with an interpretive strategy team
to include multiple voices to get different

00:07:30.850 --> 00:07:34.380
perspectives on the exhibit.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:44.280
We also work with other materials in our collections
like the archives to maybe put more context

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:48.920
to a show, give it some historical context.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:56.500
I think, again, it's about that process, that
collaborative process that we're trying to engage.

00:07:56.510 --> 00:08:04.000
We're trying to think about all the different ways
that an audience can connect into the exhibition.

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:05.050
Yeah.

00:08:05.050 --> 00:08:10.500
I mean, also to just jump on that with some
specifics, I think questions of scale, varying

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:17.850
scale, how sound and video are incorporated,
often, we sort of can consider the entire

00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:20.830
soundscape of the gallery as another layer.

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:24.350
Color is an obvious one.

00:08:24.350 --> 00:08:27.880
So, it's a great question.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:31.860
Let's see.

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:38.820
From Instagram, chezfoxyjam asks, "If
MoMA published a book on its principles of

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:43.100
Exhibition Design, what would be
the most surprising insight?"

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:50.920
I think that one of the most surprising
insights would be, in exhibition design

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:58.260
there's so many, again, so many different
people that go into making the exhibition.

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:03.180
I think that might be surprising, that
it's not about a singular person.

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:07.400
It's not about this kind of
singular attribution of authorship.

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:13.700
I think that there are so many people that
contribute. That might be surprising.

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:17.410
Like I really think that it's
a collective process.

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:20.699
Can you think of other things?

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:23.960
It seems right to me.

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:34.300
From Manny.

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:36.060
The question is, "Hello.

00:09:36.060 --> 00:09:37.300
Love the channel.

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:42.420
My question is how does architecture play
into the designing of an exhibition?

00:09:42.420 --> 00:09:45.640
Do you work with architects at all? Thanks."

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:48.740
Well, we do.

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:54.460
At the Museum of Modern Art, we do
change the architecture of the galleries.

00:09:55.550 --> 00:09:58.360
It plays a very important part.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:03.370
Mack mentioned kind of the issues of scale
and how we create environments to evoke different

00:10:03.370 --> 00:10:09.139
types of scale, like maybe grand
scales or more intimate scales.

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:12.880
We're always taking our cues from the artwork itself.

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:19.560
So it is an important part of what we do.

00:10:19.560 --> 00:10:23.459
And to the question, do we work with architects at all?

00:10:23.459 --> 00:10:26.480
That's another thing that's unique at MoMA.

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:30.160
I mean, definitely, we work with architects.

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:41.949
But we also have like a really great team of
internal staff that come from so many different

00:10:41.949 --> 00:10:49.740
backgrounds that I feel that we can.
We're always collaborating with people.

00:10:49.740 --> 00:10:57.360
So even if we do use architects, I think our team
still completely engages in the design process.

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:06.380
And I think also, just to add in, that most
of our galleries were designed as completely

00:11:06.389 --> 00:11:07.889
open spaces without partitions.

00:11:07.889 --> 00:11:11.699
Sorry, not most but a lot of our
special exhibitions galleries were.

00:11:11.699 --> 00:11:16.829
And so whenever we're putting in partitions,
considerations of egress, sprinkler coverage,

00:11:16.829 --> 00:11:23.649
lighting, come even more to the fore because
we're modifying a space that was designed

00:11:23.649 --> 00:11:25.160
as a completely open plan.

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:30.720
And we do have to maintain all the normal
things that any public space has to maintain.

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:31.720
Correct.

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:36.089
I think we're also very respectful of the
architects that are part of the building's

00:11:36.089 --> 00:11:39.589
history, of our building's history,
of our entire campus history.

00:11:39.589 --> 00:11:46.970
So there are the Taniguchi galleries that
we love the proportions of and that we often

00:11:46.970 --> 00:11:50.770
reference to create a nicely proportioned gallery.

00:11:50.770 --> 00:11:57.699
We like to respect the details
that the architect has given us.

00:11:57.699 --> 00:12:03.430
I mean, our campus is made
out of a few different buildings.

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:08.560
So among the architects that we've
gotten to know via their architecture are

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:11.000
the Goodwin/Stone building

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:14.900
has a particular feeling and
a particular architecture.

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:21.079
The Philip Johnson building has
a particular feeling as well.

00:12:21.079 --> 00:12:24.350
I mentioned the Taniguchi building.

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:31.240
And now we're in the next phase of an expansion
project, which will give us more spaces to

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:33.690
consider and to get to know.

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:36.920
Okay.

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:44.680
Alexandra via YouTube asks, "What resources,
for example books or websites, do you go to

00:12:44.680 --> 00:12:50.480
for inspiration, installation ideas,
materials, et cetera?"

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:58.780
So we do have a wonderful
resource on the MoMA website.

00:12:58.780 --> 00:13:01.880
It's the MoMA Exhibition History.

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:14.560
The MoMA Exhibition History is a full visual
catalog of all the exhibitions in MoMA's past.

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:18.040
Does it date back to 1939?

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:20.050
So it dates back to 1939.

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:24.870
And that's a fantastic resource
that anybody can tap into.

00:13:24.870 --> 00:13:27.790
There are links to the catalog when possible.

00:13:27.790 --> 00:13:34.460
And I find I'm always referencing the Exhibition
History because MoMA does have a great

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:41.999
a very robust history of exploration
and Exhibition Design.

00:13:41.999 --> 00:13:48.100
So, I love to look back at our radical
past and draw ideas from that.

00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:49.100
Yeah.

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:53.320
And I think, obviously, going to other shows.

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:59.160
And it's easy because we're in the building
but also just, the nice thing about working

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:03.990
with such a big team and we have a lot of
designers on staff, getting to see how other

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:08.300
designers even on our own team are working
with spaces that we may have worked in before.

00:14:08.300 --> 00:14:12.970
I mean, I can't tell you how many times I've
walked into a show that one of my colleagues

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:17.420
here worked on and was like, "I never
thought to do that with the skylight"

00:14:17.420 --> 00:14:19.420
or something like that.

00:14:19.420 --> 00:14:24.089
I think this building, one of the wonderful
things about these open plan galleries and

00:14:24.089 --> 00:14:30.470
the spaces that we've been given to work in
is just you've never kind of gotten through

00:14:30.470 --> 00:14:31.509
every possibility.

00:14:31.509 --> 00:14:36.389
There seems to be endless possibilities, like
as much as we get to know the spaces, which

00:14:36.389 --> 00:14:39.069
is great because it's nice to be intimate with the space.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:43.480
But then it's wonderful to be
surprised by it at the same time.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:50.580
Okay.

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:53.499
Here's the question.

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:59.040
This is a question that comes from
one of our producers I imagine.

00:15:02.060 --> 00:15:06.420
What are some of the models on the table?

00:15:06.560 --> 00:15:07.440
Okay.

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:16.060
Our team, our wonderful team of exhibition
designers, we work with models a lot.

00:15:16.069 --> 00:15:17.410
The entire team does.

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:20.220
The model's an excellent tool.

00:15:20.220 --> 00:15:23.570
And I think people can really relate to models.

00:15:23.570 --> 00:15:29.269
But we make maquettes of every
work that's in an exhibition.

00:15:29.269 --> 00:15:37.260
So we have models at half-inch scale, and a
half-inch scale is equal to a foot in real space.

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:45.680
And we have about two or three models for
every temporary exhibition gallery in the

00:15:45.689 --> 00:15:51.130
Museum so that we can work
on multiple exhibitions at a time.

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:59.490
So we make little half-inch scale models
of the artwork that's in the galleries.

00:15:59.490 --> 00:16:00.640
And I can show you some of this.

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:06.379
This is the Louise Bourgeois Spider that we
had in the atrium space of our Museum.

00:16:06.379 --> 00:16:07.850
Was that last year, Mack?

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:10.949
It was last year.

00:16:10.949 --> 00:16:16.480
And this is part of our permanent collection,
the Rachel Whiteread Water Tower, which is

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:20.620
on the roof of our building and can
be seen from the sculpture garden.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:27.240
These are scale figures, people walking in
the galleries, which is also very important.

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:34.829
It helps us understand spatially if there's
too many works on a floor, if we have enough

00:16:34.829 --> 00:16:42.910
clear pathways to move comfortably around
the artwork, and also to keep the artwork safe.

00:16:44.199 --> 00:16:48.860
I think this is a wonderful. This
is actually one inch to one foot.

00:16:48.860 --> 00:16:54.100
It's a scale model of our Brancusi.

00:16:57.720 --> 00:17:06.040
I forget the title of this work but it represents
one of the works that are currently on view

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:07.930
in our Brancusi exhibition.

00:17:07.930 --> 00:17:10.550
Did you wanna show some others?

00:17:10.550 --> 00:17:16.300
I think this is sort of a mock
model with a variety of things.

00:17:16.300 --> 00:17:23.320
So this isn't of a show but this is a real space
in the Museum and some possible works.

00:17:23.500 --> 00:17:26.820
For example, we have a Charles White here.

00:17:26.820 --> 00:17:36.100
See, often we print the name
of the artist on the back.

00:17:36.100 --> 00:17:37.260
Yeah.

00:17:37.260 --> 00:17:38.540
This is how we work.

00:17:38.540 --> 00:17:40.220
We move things around.

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:42.800
We see how they feel.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:49.820
The lovely thing about the iPhone is that its camera
is almost perfectly at scale eye-level height.

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:55.280
So you can actually take your phone and kind
of make a video walking through the model

00:17:55.280 --> 00:18:05.820
and that ends up being almost as good as a
digital rendering but without all the work.

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:13.480
And we also have a nice connection to the
database that stores all the images of the

00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:20.370
works in our collection so that when we
make these maquettes, we can actually

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:28.120
There's like a program that draws the images from
our database and puts them right into AutoCAD

00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:30.370
at a one-to-one scale.

00:18:30.370 --> 00:18:34.590
And then we print them out at
whatever scale we need for a model.

00:18:34.590 --> 00:18:39.450
That's very helpful in quickly
iterating through these models.

00:18:39.450 --> 00:18:47.120
The other thing about the maquettes that I
wanted to note was that, as you can see, there's

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:51.690
so many different styles of maquette-making.

00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:54.500
It's a wonderful way to really study an object.

00:18:54.500 --> 00:18:59.360
I think it keeps us in touch with our
process with what we are as makers.

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:08.080
I think it's a good way to just study an object
and I think really think about what's evoking

00:19:08.080 --> 00:19:13.150
the most salient features of a particular object.

00:19:13.150 --> 00:19:17.080
I really personally love making models.

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:19.390
It's my secret retirement plan.

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:23.260
It's a good one.

00:19:27.120 --> 00:19:28.300
Oh, this is for me, right?

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:29.660
You did the last one?

