00:31:11.690 --> 00:31:15.850
How do you manage traffic flow through exhibitions?

00:31:15.850 --> 00:31:20.840
How do you balance the need for people to
contemplate work versus avoiding bottlenecks?

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:23.770
That's a great question.

00:31:25.580 --> 00:31:27.220
Well, we have good partners in this.

00:31:27.240 --> 00:31:30.520
We have excellent security team.

00:31:38.840 --> 00:31:45.610
Like the question suggests, it's really about
achieving a balance and it can be pretty tricky.

00:31:45.610 --> 00:31:54.771
We'd like to create environments that are
appropriate for the artwork, of course, but

00:31:54.771 --> 00:32:02.720
we also have those practical considerations
that the Museum has about 6,000 visitors,

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:03.890
average of.

00:32:03.890 --> 00:32:05.640
Six or eight.

00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:06.660
Six or eight, six to eight.

00:32:06.660 --> 00:32:13.520
And we can actually experience numbers
far greater than that during busy days.

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:22.650
We try to keep certain distances
away from the artwork, for sure.

00:32:22.650 --> 00:32:23.970
We try to keep clear pathways.

00:32:23.970 --> 00:32:30.190
I mean, these pathways are also...not only
are they good for visitor flow, but they're

00:32:30.190 --> 00:32:36.000
good for art movement as well because there's
the practical concern of installing the artwork.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:38.830
So we do have to keep clear path work.

00:32:38.830 --> 00:32:43.280
We just have to remember the visitor experience.

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:53.070
And so in that way, we try to design enough
space to circulate around the artwork.

00:32:53.070 --> 00:32:54.260
Right.

00:32:54.260 --> 00:33:00.550
Again, managing traffic flow or managing the
flow of people through the space is one of

00:33:00.550 --> 00:33:06.040
the chief things we're thinking about with curatorial
and all our partners in various departments.

00:33:06.040 --> 00:33:11.420
So I think it is about…it's rhythm.

00:33:11.420 --> 00:33:16.900
You can use a single-entry room
as a way to create a quieter space.

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:21.700
And sometimes we do have to have a security
officer posted at the entry to a single-entry

00:33:21.700 --> 00:33:24.520
room so that it doesn't get too full.

00:33:24.520 --> 00:33:28.560
We have had experiences where we even had
to have line management within a show.

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:29.560
This is true.

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:34.270
And that VEN security had managed beautifully.

00:33:34.270 --> 00:33:39.160
Once a certain number of people are in the
building, you can't totally prevent bottlenecks.

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:45.340
Yeah, I think the principles of Exhibition Design
and good circulation hopefully helps us.

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:49.690
We've modeled a couple different solutions
like you said, just a controlled entry and

00:33:49.690 --> 00:33:54.190
monitoring how many people
are in the gallery at a time.

00:33:54.190 --> 00:33:58.560
Those are ways in which we can manage visitor flow.

00:33:58.560 --> 00:34:05.490
I mean, sometimes, not frequently, but sometimes
outside consultants had been brought in to

00:34:05.490 --> 00:34:06.490
actually model...

00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:07.490
That's true.

00:34:07.490 --> 00:34:13.700
Human flow through an exhibition or through
a public space as we're rethinking entries.

00:34:13.700 --> 00:34:20.399
We've also reacted very quickly to times when
we are expecting high attendance where we

00:34:20.399 --> 00:34:25.429
will...for instance, when the atrium was in
installation, if we can manage to kind of

00:34:25.429 --> 00:34:32.460
open up a gallery before it's ready, if we
can just stanchion off works that are still

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:33.460
in installation.

00:34:33.460 --> 00:34:37.889
We've done that to just kind of provide some
relief, provide some more seating in the Museum.

00:34:37.889 --> 00:34:42.919
And we want everyone to have
a positive visitor experience.

00:34:42.919 --> 00:34:50.909
So we are constantly considering those things and
we're working together to figure those things out.

00:34:51.909 --> 00:34:57.440
For instance, the time that I just mentioned
that we put some more seating in the atrium.

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:01.589
I think we worked with our security,
head of security on that.

