00:35:31.690 --> 00:35:34.900
How do you choose the color
palette for an exhibition?

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:44.499
What were your favorite pieces of art
or exhibitions to work with and why?

00:35:44.499 --> 00:35:46.900
I love the color question.

00:35:46.900 --> 00:35:52.609
I think we both have different experiences to share.

00:35:52.609 --> 00:35:58.589
The color palette, it's one of the
more fun parts of our job I think.

00:35:58.589 --> 00:36:04.980
And choosing the color, the inspiration
for color can come from anywhere.

00:36:04.980 --> 00:36:10.490
It could just come from like a vision that
the curator has or that the designer has.

00:36:10.490 --> 00:36:15.210
It could come from the work itself, something
that we're trying to draw out of the work.

00:36:15.210 --> 00:36:16.490
We're always considering the work.

00:36:16.490 --> 00:36:23.710
It has to look well with the work.

00:36:23.710 --> 00:36:29.619
When you're around the work enough, a color
will just come to people like at the same time

00:36:29.619 --> 00:36:31.619
So we're all standing there looking at the artwork.

00:36:31.619 --> 00:36:35.339
There can be something that just suggests itself.

00:36:35.339 --> 00:36:40.680
I love the process that we went through with
Christian Rattemeyer on the Boetti show, the

00:36:40.680 --> 00:36:44.099
Alighiero Boetti show.

00:36:44.099 --> 00:36:50.350
And Boetti is an Italian conceptual artist
that worked in the 1960s and he used very

00:36:50.350 --> 00:36:51.770
humble materials.

00:36:51.770 --> 00:36:56.170
He used cardboard and paper and aluminum.

00:36:56.170 --> 00:37:03.160
For that first gallery, Christian actually
thought of the color of a newspaper but of

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:12.049
an Italian newspaper which is this like beautiful
peachy color that was just so wonderful and

00:37:12.049 --> 00:37:13.349
subtle and humble.

00:37:13.349 --> 00:37:20.010
It kind of had this glow to it that was so beautiful.

00:37:20.010 --> 00:37:26.299
And for the other colors in the gallery, we
drew upon Boetti's tapestries and did a little

00:37:26.299 --> 00:37:39.059
research into what yarns he used in his tapestries
and discovered that that yarn company had

00:37:39.059 --> 00:37:43.099
their original colorway and
were still making these yarns.

00:37:43.099 --> 00:37:48.690
And so we got a bunch of samples of those
yarns and we kind of drew inspiration and

00:37:48.690 --> 00:37:52.089
selected a few for the colors in the gallery.

00:37:52.089 --> 00:37:57.470
That process was just so fun and I love going
to all the yarn stores in New York City to

00:37:57.470 --> 00:38:00.099
find samples.

00:38:00.099 --> 00:38:03.300
The painters will paint us samples.

00:38:03.300 --> 00:38:06.670
Some of those are behind us.

00:38:06.670 --> 00:38:10.890
Sometimes we'll bring them out to our storage
facility in Queens to hold this color next

00:38:10.890 --> 00:38:15.079
to an artwork or we'll go into the gallery
and see how it looks with the real lighting.

00:38:15.079 --> 00:38:20.410
Sometimes you have to work with the catalogue
to see what a piece…because that's the best

00:38:20.410 --> 00:38:24.140
we're gonna get because it's coming
from a lender or something like that.

00:38:24.140 --> 00:38:27.420
And that's really important to test
it out in the galleries, like you say.

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:31.940
We often will test things like that out
and other things in the gallery.

00:38:31.940 --> 00:38:37.619
Like we'll do paint swatches right on the
wall because the lighting, of course, is important

00:38:37.619 --> 00:38:39.329
and the color of the floor.

00:38:39.329 --> 00:38:40.579
So we have terrazzo floors.

00:38:40.579 --> 00:38:42.049
We have wood floors.

00:38:42.049 --> 00:38:48.980
And so we really try to test the color before choosing it.

00:38:48.980 --> 00:38:54.789
And another thing that is wonderful about
this color choosing process is the way people

00:38:54.789 --> 00:39:01.869
describe color and the way like it's in their
heads and like you'll hear curators wax poetically

00:39:01.869 --> 00:39:04.930
about like the color of a faded rose petal.

00:39:04.930 --> 00:39:06.539
Yeah, it's just wonderful.

00:39:06.539 --> 00:39:09.770
It's like you're writing the poem of colors.

00:39:09.770 --> 00:39:14.849
It's just like beautiful and wonderful
to get inspiration from that.

00:39:14.849 --> 00:39:23.490
And then favorite pieces of art or
exhibitions to work with and why?

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:25.049
Oh, man.

00:39:25.049 --> 00:39:27.299
That's a tough question.

00:39:27.299 --> 00:39:31.900
So many, and I think...I still haven't gotten
to work with the piece of art that if you

00:39:31.900 --> 00:39:35.549
had asked me when I started, I was
most looking forward to working with.

00:39:35.549 --> 00:39:37.359
I won't mention it by name.

00:39:37.359 --> 00:39:42.769
But I was actually thinking about Walid Raad's,
I think it's called Scratching on Things

00:39:42.769 --> 00:39:51.010
I Could Disavow, which was an entire stage
set and performance that sort of comprises

00:39:51.010 --> 00:39:52.010
a single work.

00:39:52.010 --> 00:39:58.390
And I was just remembering how much
fun that was to work on, how complicated.

00:39:58.390 --> 00:40:02.880
Matthew and I worked on that together and
had to actually divide up different components

00:40:02.880 --> 00:40:07.410
because it was so complicated and it went
everything from an actual sculptural object

00:40:07.410 --> 00:40:13.940
to an exhibition copy to a collaboration with
our carpentry and painting teams on like tearing

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:17.640
up a wall, just in that one piece.

00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:21.400
And then our handlers hanging artwork high up.

00:40:21.400 --> 00:40:27.119
Like on that one piece in the atrium was kind
of everyone's work and then being used by

00:40:27.119 --> 00:40:33.230
the artist as a performance space to lead
visitors through, not just creating

00:40:33.230 --> 00:40:35.230
Very full process.

00:40:37.839 --> 00:40:40.720
So that's one that I would…

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:42.160
That's great.

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:54.320
Alison Spangler asks, "Can you speak to
collaborating with artists on Exhibition Design?

00:40:54.320 --> 00:40:56.509
Any fun anecdotes."

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:08.080
Actually, working with an artist is one of
the most exciting and interesting things that

00:41:08.099 --> 00:41:09.499
we do, I think.

00:41:09.499 --> 00:41:13.599
And you just described working with Walid Raad.

00:41:13.599 --> 00:41:19.920
I loved working with Robert Gober
who is an artist that I had

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:32.089
I saw his installation at Dia in 1990
something and it just impressed upon

00:41:32.089 --> 00:41:33.430
me so much.

00:41:33.430 --> 00:41:39.650
I mean, I found, I saved the
little brochure that it...

00:41:39.650 --> 00:41:43.410
I was like going through some things
and I saved a brochure from it.

00:41:43.410 --> 00:41:52.829
And so when we were doing our show of his
work here at the Museum, I was just so thrilled.

00:41:52.829 --> 00:41:58.900
I think it was such a memorable experience.

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:07.210
I think the generosity of the artist when you're
working with them, how they put themselves

00:42:07.210 --> 00:42:15.829
out there and they invite you into their process,
which I feel is such a gift and I always feel

00:42:15.840 --> 00:42:18.120
honored when that happens.

00:42:21.520 --> 00:42:27.150
I love working with artists and all the decisions become

00:42:27.150 --> 00:42:30.539
There's a million decisions
that go into making an exhibition.

00:42:30.539 --> 00:42:41.349
And I just love the thinking around all those
decisions and really getting to know the process

00:42:41.349 --> 00:42:45.540
and the artist as a result.

00:42:45.540 --> 00:42:47.600
It's pretty indescribable.

00:42:50.400 --> 00:42:51.500
I'm sorry.

00:42:51.500 --> 00:42:56.309
Did you want to share something
like about working with an artist?

00:42:56.309 --> 00:42:57.589
I mean, you've also worked with...

00:42:57.589 --> 00:42:58.589
Its' great.

00:42:58.589 --> 00:43:06.170
It's really one of the prime joys, is working
with the people we work with and artists are

00:43:06.170 --> 00:43:08.240
among them.

00:43:08.240 --> 00:43:14.700
I remember there was a show where the artist
had blintzes brought almost daily so that

00:43:14.700 --> 00:43:20.150
they didn't have to leave the floor and we
had to set up an area and make sure CBS was

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:23.289
on board and keep it away from the artwork.

00:43:23.289 --> 00:43:28.349
It turned out one of the artists I worked
with once was a college friend of my dad's

00:43:28.349 --> 00:43:29.349
best friend.

00:43:29.349 --> 00:43:31.490
So that was kind of hilarious.

00:43:31.490 --> 00:43:32.800
And I managed to bring him to the opening.

00:43:37.400 --> 00:43:42.880
It's that thing where when you're working
with people collaboratively and things are

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:50.920
going well, it stops being, oh my God, this person

00:43:50.930 --> 00:43:54.650
And it goes from Robert Gober to Bob.

00:43:54.650 --> 00:43:57.119
And it goes from Lana Hum to Lana.

00:43:57.119 --> 00:44:01.339
It goes from Brian Rana to Brina.

00:44:01.339 --> 00:44:02.999
Not Brina, to Brian.

00:44:02.999 --> 00:44:04.640
That got weird.

00:44:04.640 --> 00:44:08.019
At a certain point, everyone's just talking.

00:44:08.019 --> 00:44:11.790
I mean, going back to Walid, I remember when
he talked about Kenny the painter because

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:16.269
Kenny was touching up his wall every
day and like they became friendly.

00:44:16.269 --> 00:44:22.349
I think that's one of the beautiful things
about the way we work is just that some of

00:44:22.360 --> 00:44:27.360
those barriers fall away and we all
get to like do good work together.

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:28.800
That's right.

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:32.880
reid.dickie

00:44:32.880 --> 00:44:38.560
How closely do you work with curators
and what is involved in those interactions?

00:44:39.120 --> 00:44:41.040
You wanna talk about that, Mack?

00:44:41.050 --> 00:44:46.359
I think as we've sort of been saying all along,
it is a very close collaboration when it gets

00:44:46.359 --> 00:44:49.589
to the Exhibition Design component.

00:44:49.600 --> 00:44:57.000
There are many other components of an exhibition
besides the actual physical gallery realization.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:06.800
For example, on a show like this, which isn't
a show, all our hands will be in there.

00:45:06.800 --> 00:45:08.380
I mean, that's how close.

00:45:08.380 --> 00:45:11.910
My hand will be here and someone
else's hand will be there.

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:13.400
And that's how closely we're working.

00:45:13.400 --> 00:45:14.120
Yeah.

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:23.200
I think the curatorial process, again, I feel
lucky that we're also invited into that process.

00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:31.319
And I think that we do work very closely
from ideas right into execution.

00:45:31.319 --> 00:45:37.519
And all those practical things, those production-related
things, like the making of the show, I think

00:45:37.519 --> 00:45:42.730
we work all the way through from just thinking
about the big concept until the last pieces

00:45:42.730 --> 00:45:44.760
hung on the wall or installed.

00:45:53.520 --> 00:45:54.520
No.

